"Van Hoek A.H.A.M., Van Alen T.A., Vogels G.D., Hackstein J.H.P.","Contribution by the methanogenic endosymbionts of anaerobic ciliates to methane production in Dutch freshwater sediments",2006,"Acta Protozoologica","45","3",,"215","224",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33748337968&partnerID=40&md5=fa8e54554577a6ecbddeee957edff9e5","Department of Evolutionary Microbiology, Faculty of Science, Radboud University Nijmegen, Nijmegen, Netherlands; Department of Evolutionary Microbiology, Faculty of Science, Radboud University Nijmegen, Toernooiveld 1, NL-6525ED Nijmegen, Netherlands; RIKILT Institute of Food Safety, Bornsesteeg 45, NL-6708PD, Wageningen, Netherlands","Van Hoek, A.H.A.M., Department of Evolutionary Microbiology, Faculty of Science, Radboud University Nijmegen, Nijmegen, Netherlands, RIKILT Institute of Food Safety, Bornsesteeg 45, NL-6708PD, Wageningen, Netherlands; Van Alen, T.A., Department of Evolutionary Microbiology, Faculty of Science, Radboud University Nijmegen, Nijmegen, Netherlands; Vogels, G.D., Department of Evolutionary Microbiology, Faculty of Science, Radboud University Nijmegen, Nijmegen, Netherlands; Hackstein, J.H.P., Department of Evolutionary Microbiology, Faculty of Science, Radboud University Nijmegen, Nijmegen, Netherlands, Department of Evolutionary Microbiology, Faculty of Science, Radboud University Nijmegen, Toernooiveld 1, NL-6525ED Nijmegen, Netherlands","Biogenic methane contributes substantially to the atmospheric methane concentration and thus to global warming. This trace gas is predominantly produced by strictly anaerobic methanogenic archaea, which thrive in the most divergent ecological niches, e. g. paddy fields, sediments, landfills, and the digestive tract of various animals. Methanogenic archaea also live as endosymbionts in the cytoplasm of anaerobic protozoa. In marine sediments these endosymbionts can contribute up to 90% to the overall rate of methanogenesis, whereas their role of in freshwater sediments is largely unknown. Here we describe the results of a one year's survey of the methanogenesis by endosymbiotic methanogens in four different Dutch freshwater sediments. The abundance of anaerobic protozoa, in particular ciliates, the methane production rates by the ecosystem and by the protists, and a number of abiotic parameters were measured. A novel method (heatshock for 5 min) for estimating the contribution by endosymbiotic methanogens was established. Our results reveal large fluctuations of ciliate abundance throughout the year, but on average, only minor contributions by methanogenic endosymbionts to the total methanogenesis in these environments.","Anaerobic ciliates; Endosymbionts; Freshwater sediments; Methanogenesis; Single cell PCR; SSU rRNA","Animalia; Archaea; Ciliophora; Methanobacteriales; Protista; Protozoa",,,,,,"Chynoweth, D.P., Environmental impact of biomethanogenesis (1996) Environ. Monit. Assessm., 42, pp. 3-18; Crutzen, P.J., Aselmann, I., Seiler, W., Methane production by domestic animals, wild ruminants, other herbivorous fauna and humans (1986) Tellus, 38 B, pp. 271-284; Doddema, H.J., Vogels, G.D., Improved identification of methanogenic bacteria by fluorescence microscopy (1978) Appl. Environ. Microbiol., 36, pp. 752-754; Embley, T.M., Van Der Giezen, M., Horner, D.S., Dyal, P.L., Foster, P., Mitochondria and hydrogenosomes are two forms of the same fundamental organelle (2003) Phil. Trans. R. Soc. London, Ser. B, 358, pp. 191-201; Esteban, G., Guhl, B.E., Clarke, K.J., Embley, T.M., Finlay, B.J., Cyclidium porcatum n. sp.: A free-living anaerobic scuticociliate containing a stable complex of hydrogenosomes, eubacteria and archaeobacteria (1993) Eur. J. Protist., 29, pp. 262-270; Felsenstein, J., Confidence limits on phylogenies: An approach using the bootstrap (1985) Evolution, 39, pp. 783-791; Fenchel, T., Methanogenesis in marine shallow water sediments: The quantitative role of anaerobic protozoa with endosymbiotic m